            h2 How can communities test their ideas?

            div(style="margin-top:40px;") We all have intuitions about our lives. Does eating a particular cereal for breakfast give me more energy? Does doing yoga help me sleep better at night? Is wine with dinner really good for my health?

            br
            h4 People's tracking can yield incorrect/incomplete results

            div(style="margin-top:20px;") To test our intuitions, we often make some changes in our lifestyle, and then observe the effects of those changes. For example, consider Janet, who thinks that her habit of drinking a cup of coffee every night negatively affects her sleep cycle. She switches to decaf for a week and collects data about how long she slept. But her measurements show that she's actually sleeping less after switching to decaf! Janet realises that there could be a number of factors that could be affecting her sleep - she could’ve been staying up late, binge watching the latest season of WestWorld, or her neighbours could’ve been particularly loud that week, or it could be that she increased her soda intake which has high amounts of caffeine too.


            div(style="margin-top:20px;") Such unsystematic tracking activities often yield wrong, or frustrating results. #[i So what could Janet do to know for sure that avoiding coffee at night could really help improve her sleep schedule?]

            br
